13
00:06:48,513 --> 00:06:59,965
[SPEAKER_01]: Thanks also to Kevin Harrington and Medford Community Media for guiding us as we broadcast to you via Medford Community Media channels nine for Comcast and 47 for Verizon.

14
00:07:00,446 --> 00:07:09,756
[SPEAKER_01]: If you're out there watching on your electronic devices, your 60 inch screens, whatever it might be, welcome to the show.

15
00:07:11,127 --> 00:07:26,058
[SPEAKER_01]: So in my travels as a poet and as an ambassador for the arts, I've been privileged to encounter some tremendous teachers, leaders, and history makers across a wide panorama of human endeavor.

16
00:07:26,639 --> 00:07:32,223
[SPEAKER_01]: Words and music has given me that opportunity to bring a lot of those folks to your attention.

17
00:07:32,743 --> 00:07:37,166
[SPEAKER_01]: Tonight is no exception, so I hope you're ready for something really special.

18
00:07:38,147 --> 00:07:46,145
[SPEAKER_01]: Our guest for this portion of the evening's program is my friend and a woman who can truly be considered a history maker.

19
00:07:46,546 --> 00:07:47,949
[SPEAKER_01]: Let me tell you a bit about her.

20
00:07:49,144 --> 00:08:02,647
[SPEAKER_01]: Dr. Sheila E. Nutt, two Ts, is a Newton resident and a former director of educational outreach programs for Harvard Medical School's Office of Diversity, Inclusion, and Community Partnership.

21
00:08:03,348 --> 00:08:08,769
[SPEAKER_01]: My wife, Teresa, worked with her for a number of years, and we met through that relationship.

22
00:08:09,509 --> 00:08:31,728
[SPEAKER_01]: Our paths crossed on a regular basis as I volunteered annually for a community-based student engagement event called Reflection in Action, a program that examined health disparities in the inner city and brought together students for greater agency and understanding in combating these inequities.

23
00:08:32,248 --> 00:08:37,051
[SPEAKER_01]: That program, in and of itself, could certainly be considered history-making.

24
00:08:37,531 --> 00:08:49,059
[SPEAKER_01]: And yet, Dr. Sheila, as she has been known affectionately by closest and dearest, made history long before her tenure at Harvard, a tenure which she retired from several years ago.

25
00:08:50,478 --> 00:09:01,266
[SPEAKER_01]: So in 1970, Sheila Nutt became one of the first African-American flight attendants working for Pan American World Airways.

26
00:09:02,067 --> 00:09:07,551
[SPEAKER_01]: Over 50 years have passed since Sheila helped make that history.

27
00:09:08,192 --> 00:09:15,997
[SPEAKER_01]: She was part of the first wave of African-American women hired as stewardesses, as they were called back then.

28
00:09:17,074 --> 00:09:22,899
[SPEAKER_01]: A half century ago, flight crews were mainly white, as were the passengers.

29
00:09:23,540 --> 00:09:29,305
[SPEAKER_01]: After the Civil Rights Act of 1964, airlines had to start hiring people of color.

30
00:09:31,327 --> 00:09:39,274
[SPEAKER_01]: In 1969, when Dr. Sheila was 20 years old and living in Philadelphia, she heard Pan Am was hiring and wanted in.

31
00:09:40,775 --> 00:09:47,541
[SPEAKER_01]: Let's explore that history with Sheila, but make sure your tray tables are locked and your seats are in the upright position.

32
00:09:47,561 --> 00:09:50,303
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, and there might be some turbulence ahead.

33
00:09:51,761 --> 00:10:11,445
[SPEAKER_01]: So as is my custom in hosting these evenings, I'd like to share a piece of verse that I shared with Dr. Sheila several years ago when she was doing some work on her program involving her colleagues and her history with PNM.

34
00:10:12,045 --> 00:10:16,866
[SPEAKER_01]: And that piece of poetry is called Song of the Blackbirds.

35
00:10:22,782 --> 00:10:24,643
[SPEAKER_01]: We are called the Blackbirds.

36
00:10:25,083 --> 00:10:29,085
[SPEAKER_01]: It has a ring that speaks to our natural woman thing.

37
00:10:29,646 --> 00:10:35,448
[SPEAKER_01]: Pin M said yes and got the best as chocolate doves embraced the test.

38
00:10:36,209 --> 00:10:39,470
[SPEAKER_01]: Not willowy blondes or buxom brunettes.

39
00:10:39,911 --> 00:10:42,052
[SPEAKER_01]: We Blackbirds flew beyond regrets.

40
00:10:42,532 --> 00:10:47,815
[SPEAKER_01]: We filled those uniforms just as well and answered that lofty airborne bell.

41
00:10:48,356 --> 00:10:55,500
[SPEAKER_01]: To serve with dignity and distinction, service like this is close to extinction.

42
00:10:55,520 --> 00:11:01,584
[SPEAKER_01]: 35,000 feet in the air, we were a flight crew beyond compare, telling the nations we weren't just white.

43
00:11:02,164 --> 00:11:04,966
[SPEAKER_01]: Through work and worth, we all took flight.

44
00:11:05,606 --> 00:11:09,309
[SPEAKER_01]: Ebony, tan, and caramel sweet, lovely sisters.

45
00:11:10,149 --> 00:11:11,270
[SPEAKER_01]: whole and complete.

46
00:11:11,870 --> 00:11:21,614
[SPEAKER_01]: Though attitude might be detected, we made our flyers feel safe and respected, rising above the scorn and disdain, striving to make our excellence plain.

47
00:11:22,414 --> 00:11:26,296
[SPEAKER_01]: Only the well-to-do flew with us, and rich folks really make a fuss.

48
00:11:27,336 --> 00:11:29,217
[SPEAKER_01]: We had to be humble right from the start.

49
00:11:29,257 --> 00:11:31,399
[SPEAKER_01]: We had to be pretty, resourceful, and smart.

50
00:11:31,759 --> 00:11:36,642
[SPEAKER_01]: Like nurses, we treated our patients well, even the ones that gave us hell.

51
00:11:37,283 --> 00:11:46,229
[SPEAKER_01]: The smallest kindnesses we would make, like mixing a traveler's cold milkshake or fluffing the pillow of a boar whose ignorance we must endure.

52
00:11:46,809 --> 00:11:49,111
[SPEAKER_01]: Yet class and dignity ruled the day.

53
00:11:49,251 --> 00:11:51,633
[SPEAKER_01]: That is the enduring Blackbird way.

54
00:11:52,333 --> 00:12:02,562
[SPEAKER_01]: Traveling the globe on speeding jets, circling the world as good as it gets, exploring exotic ports of call, winter and spring, summer and fall.

55
00:12:03,142 --> 00:12:08,246
[SPEAKER_01]: Aboard that luxury 747, just a whisper away from heaven.

56
00:12:08,847 --> 00:12:12,810
[SPEAKER_01]: We show white folks a grace unknown in all the flights they'd ever flown.

57
00:12:12,950 --> 00:12:16,113
[SPEAKER_01]: Pan Am said, yes, let's give them wings.

58
00:12:16,573 --> 00:12:19,275
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll see just what their color brings.

59
00:12:19,915 --> 00:12:26,340
[SPEAKER_01]: Just call us Blackbirds and hear the ring that speaks to a sister's natural swing.

60
00:12:26,780 --> 00:12:28,482
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, call us Blackbirds.

61
00:12:28,762 --> 00:12:29,723
[SPEAKER_01]: It has that ring.

62
00:12:30,163 --> 00:12:32,464
[SPEAKER_01]: It speaks to our natural woman thing.

63
