71
00:12:44,052 --> 00:12:57,664
[SPEAKER_03]: The Blackbirds, a group that I founded in 1918, we had a gathering of Blackbirds at Harvard Medical School.

72
00:12:58,705 --> 00:13:03,790
[SPEAKER_03]: And I called upon my wordsmith friend,

73
00:13:05,251 --> 00:13:21,931
[SPEAKER_03]: Mr. Terry to bring a little class, a little more class to the event and see if he could create a poem for us and this is what he came up with and I think it's fabulous and I think he deserves another round of applause.

74
00:13:26,164 --> 00:13:28,925
[SPEAKER_01]: All right, so let's dive right into this.

75
00:13:29,445 --> 00:13:37,148
[SPEAKER_01]: Dr. Shill, you've done a number of interviews with the news media, including WBUR and CNN, among others.

76
00:13:37,609 --> 00:13:44,991
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm always locked in on your pursuit of the opportunity to work with Pan Am as a 20-year-old college graduate.

77
00:13:45,051 --> 00:13:48,853
[SPEAKER_01]: So can you talk about your initial interview with Pan Am?

78
00:13:50,279 --> 00:13:53,241
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, let's go back just a little bit.

79
00:13:54,121 --> 00:13:58,404
[SPEAKER_03]: I graduated from the Philadelphia High School for Girls in 1966.

80
00:13:59,044 --> 00:14:02,486
[SPEAKER_03]: You can do the math, okay, and figure out how old I am.

81
00:14:03,286 --> 00:14:09,090
[SPEAKER_03]: It was the only exam school for girls in Philadelphia at the time.

82
00:14:10,063 --> 00:14:14,927
[SPEAKER_03]: There were very few of us women of color or young girls of color at that time.

83
00:14:15,487 --> 00:14:19,911
[SPEAKER_03]: And we were all programmed to go to college, post high school.

84
00:14:20,611 --> 00:14:33,602
[SPEAKER_03]: However, when we were encouraged or when we had the interviews and the conversations with our guidance counselors, many of us were told, oh, you're going to make a fabulous

85
00:14:35,203 --> 00:14:36,305
[SPEAKER_03]: dental hygienists.

86
00:14:36,385 --> 00:14:41,754
[SPEAKER_03]: You're going to make a fabulous beauty parlor somebody or another.

87
00:14:41,834 --> 00:14:49,826
[SPEAKER_03]: And so when we went home to our parents and said, you know, this is what they're guiding us towards,

88
00:14:50,527 --> 00:14:54,529
[SPEAKER_03]: Our parents were like, oh, no, that's not how we roll.

89
00:14:55,590 --> 00:15:02,374
[SPEAKER_03]: Some of us were third generation college graduates who had been to HBCUs.

90
00:15:03,034 --> 00:15:04,555
[SPEAKER_03]: They were professionals.

91
00:15:04,936 --> 00:15:07,257
[SPEAKER_03]: And it was like, oh, no, no, that's not how we roll.

92
00:15:07,737 --> 00:15:12,260
[SPEAKER_03]: However, I always wanted to be an actress.

93
00:15:14,391 --> 00:15:18,092
[SPEAKER_03]: In 66, I wanted to be a ballerina.

94
00:15:18,692 --> 00:15:22,753
[SPEAKER_03]: And I was told that there was no future for a black ballerina.

95
00:15:23,253 --> 00:15:27,874
[SPEAKER_03]: That was just the beginning of the dance companies like Alvin Ailey.

96
00:15:28,474 --> 00:15:31,014
[SPEAKER_03]: And so I believed that.

97
00:15:31,514 --> 00:15:34,415
[SPEAKER_03]: And I said, well, I'm going to be an actress and a model.

98
00:15:34,975 --> 00:15:36,015
[SPEAKER_03]: How do I do that?

99
00:15:36,715 --> 00:15:41,136
[SPEAKER_03]: So I entered the Miss America contest in Philadelphia.

100
00:15:42,490 --> 00:16:01,341
[SPEAKER_03]: In 1968, I was the only black to enter the contest, and that particular contest was the first step towards getting to the main Miss America contest that takes place in September in Atlantic City, New Jersey.

101
00:16:03,019 --> 00:16:14,683
[SPEAKER_03]: I prepared, I was excited, and I was thinking, oh boy, if I win, I'm gonna get discovered, and I will go to Hollywood, and oh, I was just, I had it.

102
00:16:16,344 --> 00:16:28,968
[SPEAKER_03]: So, the evening came, I was prepared, and I was one of the few participants standing as they were calling who was the winner.

103
00:16:30,482 --> 00:16:34,984
[SPEAKER_03]: So they did third runner-up, second runner-up, and I'm still standing.

104
00:16:35,164 --> 00:16:36,645
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, there's a chance.

105
00:16:37,385 --> 00:16:41,147
[SPEAKER_03]: And then they came to first runner-up, and that was my name.

106
00:16:41,167 --> 00:16:46,049
[SPEAKER_03]: I was a little pissed, but you know, I'm black.

107
00:16:46,189 --> 00:16:48,310
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm happy for first runner-up.

108
00:16:48,730 --> 00:16:50,651
[SPEAKER_03]: And then they announced the queen.

109
00:16:51,471 --> 00:16:55,853
[SPEAKER_03]: And so we all took photographs, and we were happy and bubbly.

110
00:16:57,214 --> 00:16:59,135
[SPEAKER_03]: So when we're leaving the venue,

111
00:17:00,680 --> 00:17:07,122
[SPEAKER_03]: One of the judges came to my parents and me and asked if they could talk to my mother in private.

112
00:17:07,243 --> 00:17:18,487
[SPEAKER_03]: They pulled her over to the side and they said, we were unanimous in our choice of the queen.

113
00:17:19,507 --> 00:17:26,650
[SPEAKER_03]: We really wanted Sheila to win, but we weren't ready for a black queen.

114
00:17:33,484 --> 00:17:36,547
[SPEAKER_03]: Let that sink in a minute.

115
00:17:36,927 --> 00:17:39,189
[SPEAKER_03]: They weren't ready for a black queen.

116
00:17:40,690 --> 00:17:44,773
[SPEAKER_03]: Not because my talent wasn't good enough.

117
00:17:45,534 --> 00:17:49,337
[SPEAKER_03]: Not because I didn't answer the questions professionally.

118
00:17:51,659 --> 00:17:56,843
[SPEAKER_03]: But because of the color of my skin that God had given me.

119
00:17:58,964 --> 00:18:00,325
[SPEAKER_03]: So I was a little annoyed.

120
00:18:00,345 --> 00:18:02,067
[SPEAKER_03]: I was a little angry.

121
00:18:03,639 --> 00:18:16,207
[SPEAKER_03]: And what really was happening here was if anything had happened to the queen, I would become queen by default.

122
00:18:16,227 --> 00:18:20,150
[SPEAKER_04]: Anyway.

123
00:18:27,543 --> 00:18:30,344
[SPEAKER_03]: So I get, no.

124
00:18:32,364 --> 00:18:34,344
[SPEAKER_03]: I was happy to be first runner up.

125
00:18:35,585 --> 00:18:44,767
[SPEAKER_03]: So it just so happened that the person who was Miss Congeniality, she said, Sheila, I know you want to be discovered.

126
00:18:45,227 --> 00:18:47,247
[SPEAKER_03]: She said, the airlines are hiring.

127
00:18:47,667 --> 00:18:49,628
[SPEAKER_03]: Maybe you'll get discovered on an airplane.

128
00:18:49,988 --> 00:18:51,108
[SPEAKER_03]: I said, okay, fine.

129
00:18:51,668 --> 00:18:55,269
[SPEAKER_03]: So my friend Sandy and I were, you know, this is the 60s.

130
00:18:56,249 --> 00:19:03,892
[SPEAKER_03]: This is Vietnam War, this is Roe versus Wade, this is burn your bra, this is, you know, Kent State.

131
00:19:04,012 --> 00:19:06,173
[SPEAKER_03]: This is tumultuous times.

132
00:19:06,593 --> 00:19:07,534
[SPEAKER_03]: Contraceptives.

133
00:19:07,854 --> 00:19:13,236
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, you know, so we were really active, for lack of a better word.

134
00:19:13,936 --> 00:19:17,398
[SPEAKER_03]: So Sandy and I looked in the

135
00:19:18,687 --> 00:19:35,863
[SPEAKER_03]: Sunday newspaper that's where you know, that's the equivalent of Craigslist So you look in the Sunday paper in the one at section and so we looked under airlines and the only airlines we saw was Pan American World Airways

136
00:19:36,423 --> 00:19:38,305
[SPEAKER_03]: So Sandy and I said, well, let's go for it.

137
00:19:38,345 --> 00:19:41,608
[SPEAKER_03]: We called up for an interview date.

138
00:19:42,309 --> 00:19:48,816
[SPEAKER_03]: And the lady said, before we can give you an interview date, you have to pass certain requirements.

139
00:19:49,416 --> 00:19:54,501
[SPEAKER_03]: You had to be a certain height, a certain weight, no eyeglasses, no braces, no acne.

140
00:19:55,542 --> 00:19:57,865
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, it was just a bunch of no's.

141
00:19:57,945 --> 00:20:00,227
[SPEAKER_03]: However, you had to be college educated.

142
00:20:00,708 --> 00:20:02,670
[SPEAKER_03]: You had to have a second language.

143
00:20:02,690 --> 00:20:07,175
[SPEAKER_03]: You had to be at least 21, not married, no kids.

144
00:20:07,315 --> 00:20:08,476
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, it's on and on.

145
00:20:09,077 --> 00:20:10,438
[SPEAKER_03]: So we said, okay, we're fine.

146
00:20:11,839 --> 00:20:13,041
[SPEAKER_03]: We got an interview date.

147
00:20:13,882 --> 00:20:16,444
[SPEAKER_03]: And the two of us went down to a local hotel.

148
00:20:17,851 --> 00:20:29,101
[SPEAKER_03]: And when we entered the reception area, it was filled with the most beautiful women that you could ever see.

149
00:20:29,801 --> 00:20:33,124
[SPEAKER_03]: Sandy and I were the only women that looked like us in the room.

150
00:20:35,629 --> 00:20:41,574
[SPEAKER_03]: Neither of us knew about Pan Am because Pan American at the time was strictly international.

151
00:20:42,255 --> 00:20:49,080
[SPEAKER_03]: African Americans, people of color, were going from Detroit to L.A., L.A.

152
00:20:49,180 --> 00:20:53,904
[SPEAKER_03]: to Miami, but we weren't going from New York to Paris.

153
00:20:54,585 --> 00:20:56,246
[SPEAKER_03]: We just weren't, okay?

154
00:20:56,907 --> 00:21:04,012
[SPEAKER_03]: So as I sat there waiting for my interview, I read the brochure.

155
00:21:06,118 --> 00:21:08,960
[SPEAKER_03]: I looked at the brochure and I said, Paris?

156
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:10,741
[SPEAKER_03]: Istanbul?

157
00:21:11,701 --> 00:21:12,702
[SPEAKER_03]: Around the world?

158
00:21:14,203 --> 00:21:14,863
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh my gosh.

159
00:21:18,485 --> 00:21:21,607
[SPEAKER_03]: I wanted that job more than I wanted to become Miss America.

160
00:21:22,208 --> 00:21:23,228
